[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 6.9: Social Determinant Phenotyping
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Research/Production · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.15–$0.40 per patient profile
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A 62-year-old woman with diabetes shows up in the ED for the third time this quarter with uncontrolled blood sugar. Her A1C is climbing. Her care team is frustrated. They've adjusted her insulin regimen twice. They've referred her to a diabetes educator. Nothing sticks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What nobody documented in a structured field: she lost her housing six months ago. She's couch-surfing between her daughter's apartment and a friend's place. She can't refrigerate insulin reliably. She can't maintain a consistent meal schedule. The diabetes isn't the problem. The diabetes is a symptom of the problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the social determinants of health (SDOH) gap. Clinicians know intuitively that housing, food access, transportation, social isolation, and economic instability drive health outcomes. The research is overwhelming: zip code predicts life expectancy better than genetic code. But healthcare systems are terrible at capturing this information in a structured, actionable way.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's why. SDOH data lives in three places, and none of them talk to each other well:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 1. **Clinical notes.** A social worker writes "patient reports difficulty affording medications" in a progress note. A physician documents "lives alone, no family support nearby." This information is trapped in free text, invisible to analytics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 2. **Screening tools.** Some organizations use structured SDOH screeners (PRAPARE, AHC HRSN, Protocol for Responding to and Assessing Patients' Assets, Risks, and Experiences). But screening rates are low, patients don't always disclose, and the data goes stale fast.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 3. **External data.** Census tract poverty rates, food desert maps, Area Deprivation Index scores. These are population-level proxies, not individual-level truths. A wealthy person can live in a poor zip code and vice versa.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The result: health systems make clinical decisions without understanding the social context that determines whether those decisions will actually work. They cluster patients by disease, by utilization, by cost. But they rarely cluster by the social circumstances that explain why some patients thrive and others spiral.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Social determinant phenotyping is the practice of building composite profiles of patients' social circumstances by combining NLP extraction from clinical notes, structured screening data, and community-level indicators into coherent, actionable clusters. Not just "this patient has food insecurity" but "this patient belongs to a phenotype characterized by housing instability, transportation barriers, and social isolation, and patients in this phenotype respond best to community health worker outreach rather than phone-based care management."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m That's what we're building.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Clustering on Sparse, Sensitive, Multi-Modal Data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why This Is Harder Than Standard Clustering
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Standard patient clustering (Recipe 6.1 through 6.4) works on relatively clean, structured data: diagnosis codes, lab values, utilization counts. The features are numeric, complete (mostly), and well-understood. You pick a distance metric, run k-means or hierarchical clustering, and interpret the results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Social determinant phenotyping breaks every one of those assumptions:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sparsity.** Most patients don't have structured SDOH data. Screening rates at even progressive health systems hover around 20-40% of encounters. For the remaining 60-80%, you're inferring from notes, or you have nothing at all. Your feature matrix is mostly zeros and nulls, and you can't tell the difference between "screened negative for food insecurity" and "never asked about food insecurity."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-modality.** Your signal comes from at least three different data types: free-text clinical notes (unstructured), screening questionnaire responses (structured categorical), and geographic/community indicators (continuous numeric). Combining these into a single feature space requires careful engineering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal instability.** Social circumstances change. A patient who was stably housed last year may be homeless today. A patient who had reliable transportation lost it when their car broke down. SDOH phenotypes are not static labels; they're snapshots that decay in relevance over time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sensitivity and bias.** Clustering patients by social vulnerability creates categories that correlate with race, ethnicity, and socioeconomic status. If you're not careful, you build a system that effectively redlines patients. The clusters must be used to direct resources toward vulnerable populations, never to deny care or justify disparities.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### NLP Extraction: Getting Signal from Notes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first technical challenge is extracting SDOH mentions from clinical text. This is a specialized NLP problem because:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - SDOH language is indirect. Clinicians rarely write "patient is food insecure." They write "patient reports skipping meals to afford medications" or "difficulty maintaining diet due to limited grocery access."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Negation matters enormously. "Patient denies housing instability" is the opposite of "patient reports housing instability." Your NLP must handle negation correctly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Context windows matter. The relevant sentence might be buried in a 3-page social work assessment, a brief aside in a physician note, or a nursing intake form.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The standard approach uses a combination of:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 1. **Named Entity Recognition (NER)** trained on SDOH-specific ontologies. The most common taxonomy is the Gravity Project's SDOH Clinical Care standard, which defines categories like housing instability, food insecurity, transportation insecurity, financial strain, social isolation, and interpersonal violence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 2. **Assertion classification** to determine whether a detected mention is affirmed, negated, or hypothetical. "Patient has housing instability" (affirmed) vs. "patient denies housing instability" (negated) vs. "if patient loses housing" (hypothetical).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 3. **Temporal reasoning** to determine when the social circumstance was active. "Patient was homeless in 2019 but is now stably housed" should not be coded as current homelessness.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Pre-trained clinical NLP models (trained on clinical text corpora) provide a starting point, but SDOH-specific fine-tuning is almost always necessary. The vocabulary of social determinants is different from the vocabulary of clinical findings, and general clinical NER models miss most SDOH mentions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Feature Engineering: Building the Phenotype Vector
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Once you have extracted SDOH signals from notes and combined them with structured screening data and community indicators, you need to represent each patient as a feature vector suitable for clustering. The typical feature space includes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **NLP-derived features (per SDOH domain):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Binary presence/absence of each SDOH category (housing, food, transport, financial, social, safety)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Mention frequency (more mentions may indicate severity or persistence)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Recency of most recent mention
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Assertion polarity (affirmed vs. negated)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured screening features:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Screening tool responses (often Likert scales or yes/no)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Screening completion rate (itself informative: patients who refuse screening may differ systematically)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Community-level features:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Area Deprivation Index (ADI) for patient's census tract
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Food desert indicator (USDA Food Access Research Atlas)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Transportation access score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Social vulnerability index (CDC SVI)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Derived features:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - SDOH burden score (count of active domains)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Temporal trajectory (improving, stable, worsening)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Concordance between self-report and NLP extraction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Clustering Approaches for Sparse, Mixed Data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Standard k-means assumes continuous features and Euclidean distance. That's a poor fit here. Better options:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **K-prototypes** handles mixed categorical and continuous features natively. It uses Hamming distance for categorical features and Euclidean for continuous ones, with a weighting parameter to balance the two.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Gower distance with hierarchical clustering** computes pairwise distances that handle mixed types (binary, categorical, continuous) and missing values gracefully. Hierarchical clustering then builds a dendrogram you can cut at different levels to explore different granularities.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Latent class analysis (LCA)** is a model-based approach that assumes patients belong to unobserved latent classes, each with its own probability distribution over the observed features. LCA handles categorical data naturally and provides probabilistic cluster membership rather than hard assignments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Autoencoders for dimensionality reduction** can learn a compressed representation of the sparse, high-dimensional feature space, and you cluster in the latent space. This works well when you have enough data to train the encoder, but interpretability suffers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For SDOH phenotyping specifically, LCA and Gower-distance hierarchical clustering tend to work best because they handle the mixed data types and sparsity patterns without requiring imputation gymnastics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Validation: The Hard Part
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Unlike supervised learning, there's no ground truth for "correct" SDOH phenotypes. Validation requires:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 1. **Clinical face validity.** Do the clusters make intuitive sense to social workers and care managers? Can they describe the "typical patient" in each cluster?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 2. **Predictive validity.** Do the phenotypes predict outcomes that matter? Patients in the "housing instability + social isolation" cluster should have different utilization patterns, different intervention response rates, and different health trajectories than patients in the "transportation barrier only" cluster.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 3. **Stability.** If you re-run the clustering on a different time window or a different patient sample, do you get similar phenotypes? Unstable clusters aren't useful for operational decision-making.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 4. **Equity audit.** Do the clusters correlate with race/ethnicity in ways that could enable discrimination? If cluster 3 is 90% Black patients, you need to understand why and ensure the cluster is used to direct resources, not to justify disparities.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Clinical Notes] ──→ [NLP Extraction] ──→ [SDOH Feature Store]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                     ↑
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Screening Data] ──────────────────────────────────→│
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                     ↑
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Community Data] ──→ [Geocoding + Linkage] ────────→│
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                     ↓
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                           [Feature Assembly] ──→ [Clustering Engine]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                                         ↓
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                               [Phenotype Assignment]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                                         ↓
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                               [Validation + Audit]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                                         ↓
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                               [Intervention Matching]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stage 1: NLP Extraction.** Process clinical notes through an SDOH-specific NLP pipeline. Extract mentions, classify assertions, resolve temporality. Output: per-patient, per-encounter SDOH mention records with domain, polarity, and timestamp.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stage 2: Feature Assembly.** Combine NLP extractions, structured screening responses, and geocoded community indicators into a unified patient feature vector. Handle missingness explicitly (distinguish "screened negative" from "never screened"). Apply temporal weighting (recent signals matter more than old ones).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stage 3: Clustering.** Apply an appropriate clustering algorithm to the assembled feature matrix. Determine optimal cluster count through a combination of statistical criteria (silhouette score, BIC for LCA) and clinical interpretability. Assign each patient a phenotype label and a membership probability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stage 4: Validation and Audit.** Assess clinical face validity with domain experts. Test predictive validity against outcomes. Run equity analysis. Document cluster characteristics and intended use.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stage 5: Intervention Matching.** Map phenotypes to recommended intervention strategies. The "housing instability + food insecurity" phenotype gets connected to housing navigators and food assistance programs. The "transportation barrier" phenotype gets connected to ride services and telehealth options. This is where the clustering becomes actionable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Comprehend Medical for NLP extraction.** Comprehend Medical is AWS's healthcare-specific NLP service. It detects medical entities, including social history mentions, from clinical text. While it doesn't have a dedicated SDOH extraction mode, its entity detection combined with custom classification models provides the foundation. For SDOH-specific extraction beyond what Comprehend Medical handles natively, you'll supplement with Amazon SageMaker hosting a fine-tuned model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for SDOH-specific NLP and clustering.** SageMaker provides the ML infrastructure for two pieces: (1) a fine-tuned NER model for SDOH extraction that goes beyond Comprehend Medical's built-in capabilities, and (2) the clustering algorithm itself (LCA or k-prototypes). SageMaker Processing jobs handle the feature assembly and clustering computation. SageMaker endpoints serve real-time phenotype assignment for new patients.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for data lake storage.** Clinical notes, screening data, community indicator files, extracted features, and clustering results all live in S3. Organized by processing stage with lifecycle policies for PHI retention compliance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Glue for ETL and feature assembly.** Glue jobs handle the integration of multiple data sources (EHR extracts, screening databases, census data) into the unified feature matrix. Glue's schema-on-read approach handles the heterogeneous source formats without requiring a rigid upfront schema.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for phenotype assignments.** The final phenotype label for each patient needs to be queryable in real time by care management systems. DynamoDB provides single-digit-millisecond lookups by patient ID.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for orchestration.** Event-driven triggers coordinate the pipeline: new notes arrive, NLP extraction fires, features update, phenotype re-assignment runs on schedule.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Location Service for geocoding.** Converting patient addresses to coordinates and linking to census tracts for community indicator lookup.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[Clinical Notes\nEHR Extract] -->|Batch| B[S3 Data Lake\nnotes-raw/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B --> C[Lambda Trigger]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C --> D[Comprehend Medical\nEntity Extraction]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C --> E[SageMaker Endpoint\nSDOH NER Model]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D --> F[S3\nsdoh-extractions/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E --> F
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G[Screening Data\nPRAPARE/AHC] --> H[Glue ETL]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I[Patient Addresses] --> J[Location Service\nGeocoding]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J --> K[Census Tract Lookup]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     K --> H
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F --> H
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H --> L[S3\nfeature-matrix/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     L --> M[SageMaker Processing\nClustering Job]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     M --> N[S3\nphenotype-results/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     N --> O[DynamoDB\npatient-phenotypes]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     O --> P[Care Management\nIntervention Matching]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style D fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style E fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style M fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style O fill:#9f9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Comprehend Medical, Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, AWS Glue, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Lambda, Amazon Location Service |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `comprehend:DetectEntities`, `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `sagemaker:CreateProcessingJob`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `geo:SearchPlaceIndexForText` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | Required. Clinical notes and SDOH data are PHI. All services must be covered under your AWS BAA. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS for all buckets. DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default). SageMaker: KMS-encrypted training data, model artifacts, and endpoint traffic. All transit over TLS. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: SageMaker endpoints and Glue jobs in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, Comprehend Medical, and CloudWatch Logs. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for all API calls. SDOH data access must be auditable. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic clinical notes with SDOH mentions. MIMIC-III/IV contains social history sections. CDC SVI data is publicly available. Never use real patient notes in development. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Comprehend Medical: ~$0.01 per 100 characters. SageMaker endpoint: ~$0.05/hour (ml.m5.large). Glue: ~$0.44/DPU-hour. Per-patient total depends on note volume; estimate $0.15-$0.40 per patient for initial phenotyping. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Comprehend Medical** | Base NLP extraction of medical and social entities from clinical notes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Hosts fine-tuned SDOH NER model; runs clustering processing jobs; serves real-time phenotype assignment |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Data lake for notes, extractions, features, and results |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL for combining NLP output, screening data, and community indicators into feature matrix |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Real-time phenotype lookup by patient ID |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Event-driven orchestration of extraction pipeline |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Location Service** | Geocoding patient addresses to census tracts |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all PHI-containing stores |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Pipeline monitoring, extraction quality metrics, drift detection |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: NLP extraction from clinical notes.** When new clinical notes arrive in the data lake, the system extracts SDOH-relevant mentions. This is a two-pass approach: first, Amazon Comprehend Medical identifies general medical entities and social history mentions. Second, a fine-tuned SDOH-specific model (hosted on SageMaker) performs targeted extraction for the six core SDOH domains. The two-pass approach matters because Comprehend Medical catches broad patterns efficiently, while the specialized model handles the indirect, nuanced language of social determinants that general models miss. Skip this step and you're limited to the 20-40% of patients who completed structured screening tools.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SDOH_DOMAINS = ["housing", "food", "transportation", "financial", "social_isolation", "safety"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION extract_sdoh_from_note(note_text, patient_id, encounter_date):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pass 1: Use managed NLP service for broad entity detection.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This catches explicit mentions like "homeless" or "food stamps"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // and provides medical context (diagnoses, medications) that helps
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // disambiguate social mentions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     medical_entities = call ComprehendMedical.DetectEntities(Text = note_text)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Filter to social-history-relevant entities.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Comprehend Medical categorizes entities; we want the ones tagged
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // as social history, personal attributes, or behavioral factors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     social_mentions = filter medical_entities where Category in
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ["SOCIAL_DETERMINANT", "BEHAVIORAL_ENVIRONMENTAL_SOCIAL"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pass 2: Use fine-tuned SDOH NER model for nuanced extraction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This model was trained specifically on clinical text annotated
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // for SDOH mentions, including indirect language like
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // "patient reports skipping meals to pay rent."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     sdoh_extractions = call SageMaker.InvokeEndpoint(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         EndpointName = "sdoh-ner-model",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Body = note_text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Merge results from both passes, deduplicating overlapping spans.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Each extraction includes: domain, text_span, assertion (affirmed/negated),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // confidence score, and character offsets in the original note.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     merged = deduplicate_and_merge(social_mentions, sdoh_extractions)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Classify assertion status for each mention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // "Patient denies food insecurity" is NEGATED.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // "Patient reports difficulty affording food" is AFFIRMED.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // "If patient loses housing" is HYPOTHETICAL.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each mention in merged:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         mention.assertion = classify_assertion(mention.text_span, note_text)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         mention.domain = map_to_sdoh_domain(mention, SDOH_DOMAINS)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         mention.patient_id = patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         mention.encounter_date = encounter_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN merged
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Feature assembly.** This step combines three data sources into a single patient feature vector: NLP extractions from notes, structured screening responses, and community-level indicators linked via geocoding. The challenge is handling missingness honestly. A patient with no NLP mentions might have no social needs, or might simply have sparse documentation. A patient with no screening data wasn't necessarily screened negative; they may never have been asked. The feature vector must encode these distinctions because they affect clustering behavior. Treating "never screened" as "no needs" would systematically undercount SDOH burden in populations with less documentation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION assemble_patient_features(patient_id, lookback_months = 24):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features = empty map
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- NLP-derived features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pull all SDOH extractions for this patient within the lookback window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     extractions = query S3 for sdoh-extractions where
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id = patient_id AND
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         encounter_date >= (today - lookback_months)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each domain in SDOH_DOMAINS:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         domain_mentions = filter extractions where domain = domain AND assertion = "AFFIRMED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Binary: was this domain ever mentioned as present?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[domain + "_present"] = (count of domain_mentions > 0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Frequency: how often was it mentioned? More mentions suggest persistence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[domain + "_mention_count"] = count of domain_mentions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Recency: days since most recent affirmed mention. Recent = more relevant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF domain_mentions is not empty:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             features[domain + "_days_since_last"] = days between today and max(encounter_dates)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             features[domain + "_days_since_last"] = NULL  // explicitly missing, not zero
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Negation signal: was this domain explicitly screened negative?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         negated = filter extractions where domain = domain AND assertion = "NEGATED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[domain + "_negated"] = (count of negated > 0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Structured screening features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     screening = query screening database for patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF screening exists:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["screening_completed"] = TRUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["screening_date"] = screening.date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["screening_food_score"] = screening.food_insecurity_score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["screening_housing_score"] = screening.housing_instability_score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["screening_transport_score"] = screening.transportation_score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["screening_financial_score"] = screening.financial_strain_score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["screening_social_score"] = screening.social_isolation_score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["screening_safety_score"] = screening.safety_score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["screening_completed"] = FALSE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // All screening scores remain NULL (not zero)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Community-level features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     address = get most recent address for patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF address exists:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         geocode_result = call LocationService.SearchPlaceIndex(Text = address)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         census_tract = lookup_census_tract(geocode_result.coordinates)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["adi_national_rank"] = lookup_adi(census_tract)          // 1-100, higher = more deprived
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["food_desert_flag"] = lookup_food_desert(census_tract)   // binary
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["svi_overall"] = lookup_svi(census_tract)                // 0-1, higher = more vulnerable
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["svi_housing_transport"] = lookup_svi_theme(census_tract, "housing_transport")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // No address on file. Community features are NULL.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["adi_national_rank"] = NULL
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["food_desert_flag"] = NULL
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features["svi_overall"] = NULL
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // --- Derived features ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Total SDOH burden: count of domains with affirmed mentions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["sdoh_burden_count"] = count of domains where features[domain + "_present"] = TRUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Documentation density: total notes in lookback period.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Low documentation density means NLP absence is less informative.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["note_count_in_window"] = count notes for patient_id in lookback window
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features["sdoh_mention_density"] = total affirmed mentions / features["note_count_in_window"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Clustering.** With the feature matrix assembled, this step applies a clustering algorithm to discover natural groupings of patients by social determinant profile. The choice of algorithm matters: we use Gower distance (which handles mixed binary, categorical, and continuous features natively) with hierarchical agglomerative clustering. This avoids the need to impute missing values or force everything into a numeric space. The optimal number of clusters is determined by a combination of silhouette score (statistical) and clinical interpretability (human judgment). In practice, SDOH phenotyping tends to produce 4-8 meaningful clusters. Fewer than 4 is too coarse to be actionable; more than 8 is too granular for care management teams to operationalize.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION cluster_patients(feature_matrix, min_k = 4, max_k = 8):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute pairwise Gower distance matrix.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Gower distance handles mixed types:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   - Binary features: simple matching (0 if same, 1 if different)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   - Continuous features: normalized absolute difference
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   - Missing values: excluded from that pair's distance calculation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //     (distance computed only over shared non-null features)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     distance_matrix = compute_gower_distance(feature_matrix)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Try each candidate cluster count and evaluate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     best_k = min_k
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     best_score = -1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     results = empty map
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR k in range(min_k, max_k + 1):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Hierarchical agglomerative clustering with Ward's linkage.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Ward's minimizes within-cluster variance, producing compact clusters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         labels = hierarchical_cluster(distance_matrix, method = "ward", n_clusters = k)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Silhouette score: how well-separated are the clusters?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Range: -1 to 1. Higher is better. Above 0.3 is reasonable for social data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         silhouette = compute_silhouette(distance_matrix, labels)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Store results for comparison.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         results[k] = { labels: labels, silhouette: silhouette }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF silhouette > best_score:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             best_score = silhouette
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             best_k = k
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Return the best clustering for clinical review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The final k may be adjusted after clinical validation (Step 4).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN results[best_k]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Phenotype characterization and validation.** Raw cluster labels (0, 1, 2, ...) are meaningless to care teams. This step characterizes each cluster by its dominant features and assigns a human-readable phenotype name. It also runs the equity audit: checking whether clusters correlate with race/ethnicity in ways that could enable discrimination. The output is a phenotype catalog that care management teams can use to match patients to interventions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION characterize_phenotypes(feature_matrix, cluster_labels, patient_demographics):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     phenotypes = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each cluster_id in unique(cluster_labels):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cluster_patients = filter feature_matrix where label = cluster_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cluster_size = count of cluster_patients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Compute feature prevalence within this cluster.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Which SDOH domains are most common in this group?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         profile = empty map
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each domain in SDOH_DOMAINS:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             prevalence = mean of cluster_patients[domain + "_present"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             profile[domain] = prevalence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Identify dominant features (prevalence > 50% in cluster).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         dominant_domains = filter profile where prevalence > 0.5
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Compute community indicator averages.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         avg_adi = mean of cluster_patients["adi_national_rank"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         avg_svi = mean of cluster_patients["svi_overall"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // --- Equity audit ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Check demographic composition of this cluster.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cluster_demographics = filter patient_demographics where label = cluster_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         race_distribution = compute distribution of cluster_demographics.race
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Flag if any racial group is overrepresented by more than 2x
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // compared to the overall population.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         equity_flags = check_overrepresentation(race_distribution, overall_distribution, threshold = 2.0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         phenotype = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             cluster_id:       cluster_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             size:             cluster_size,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             dominant_domains: dominant_domains,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             avg_adi:          avg_adi,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             avg_svi:          avg_svi,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             equity_flags:     equity_flags,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Human-readable name assigned after clinical review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Examples: "Housing + Food Insecurity", "Transportation Barrier Only",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             //           "Multi-Domain Social Complexity", "Low Documentation / Unknown"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             name:             NULL  // assigned by clinical team in validation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append phenotype to phenotypes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN phenotypes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Store phenotype assignments.** Write each patient's phenotype assignment to the real-time lookup store. Include the assignment date, confidence (membership probability if using soft clustering), and a staleness indicator. Phenotypes decay: a patient's social circumstances change, and an assignment from 18 months ago may no longer reflect reality. Downstream systems should check the assignment date and trigger re-evaluation if it's stale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m STALENESS_THRESHOLD_DAYS = 180  // re-evaluate phenotype if older than 6 months
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION store_phenotype_assignment(patient_id, phenotype, confidence, feature_snapshot):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write to DynamoDB table "patient-phenotypes":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id       = patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         phenotype_id     = phenotype.cluster_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         phenotype_name   = phenotype.name
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         confidence       = confidence                    // membership probability (0-1)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         assigned_date    = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         dominant_domains = phenotype.dominant_domains    // for quick reference without full lookup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         feature_snapshot = feature_snapshot              // the features at time of assignment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         stale_after      = today + STALENESS_THRESHOLD_DAYS
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         version          = clustering model version     // track which model produced this
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter06.09-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample phenotype catalog (typical output from a large health system):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "phenotypes": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "cluster_id": 0,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "name": "Housing Instability + Food Insecurity",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "size": 2847,
